{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"A\n    \n      Go + PostgreSQL/PostGIS + WebSockets\n      RECOMMENDED\n      Lightweight Go backend with PostGIS for geospatial queries, WebSockets for real-time location push, and FCM for background notifications.\n      \n        \n          Pros\n          \n            Go compiles to a single binary — tiny Docker image, runs on a Pi\n            PostGIS handles geofence math (point-in-polygon) natively\n            WebSockets give instant map updates with minimal overhead\n            Low memory footprint (~20-50MB for this scale)\n            Excellent concurrency model for real-time connections\n          \n        \n        \n          Cons\n          \n            More verbose than Python/Node for CRUD operations\n            PostGIS adds complexity vs plain Postgres","choice":"a","id":null,"timestamp":1775053566787}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"B\n    \n      Node.js (Fastify) + PostgreSQL/PostGIS + Socket.io\n      JavaScript/TypeScript backend with the same PostGIS foundation, using Socket.io for real-time.\n      \n        \n          Pros\n          \n            Large ecosystem, easy to find libraries\n            Socket.io handles reconnection/fallback automatically\n            TypeScript provides good type safety\n          \n        \n        \n          Cons\n          \n            Higher memory baseline (~80-150MB with Node)\n            node_modules adds Docker image bloat\n            Single-threaded — less natural for concurrent connections","choice":"b","id":null,"timestamp":1775053570633}
